      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Also called</span><span class="meta-value">August 2018 Core Update</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>The <strong>Google Medic Update</strong> was a broad core algorithm update launched on August 1, 2018 that disproportionately impacted health, medical, wellness, and financial websites. Google never officially named it — the SEO community coined the label after its outsized effect on medical content sites. It demonstrated that E-E-A-T (Experience, Expertise, Authoritativeness, Trustworthiness) and YMYL (Your Money or Your Life) would become dominant ranking factors going forward.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Launch date</div>
            <div class="tms-value">August 1, 2018</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Traffic impact</div>
            <div class="tms-value">-40 to -70% for YMYL sites</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">The Medic Update didn't introduce a new concept — E-E-A-T signals had been in Google's quality rater guidelines for years. What it did was enforce those signals algorithmically at scale for the first time. Sites that had ranked on content volume and backlinks alone suddenly needed to prove their authors were actually qualified to give health or financial advice.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is the Google Medic Update?</h2>
        <p>The Google Medic Update is the nickname for a broad core algorithm update that rolled out on August 1, 2018. Google described it as a "broad core algorithm update" with no specific name. SEO analyst Marie Haynes identified the disproportionate impact on health and medical sites and the name "Medic Update" spread from there.</p>
        <p>The update elevated sites with strong expertise signals — named authors with listed credentials, citations to peer-reviewed research, clear editorial review processes, and organizational transparency — at the expense of sites publishing health or financial advice from anonymous or unqualified sources.</p>
        <p>Key impacts at launch:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Health advice sites without credentialed authors lost 40-70% of organic traffic</li>
          <li>Alternative medicine websites lost visibility to hospital and government health pages</li>
          <li>Financial advice blogs from anonymous authors were replaced by certified financial planner content</li>
          <li>A financial planning firm with existing CFP/CPA author bios saw traffic increase 35% without any content changes</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's stance on YMYL</div>
          <p>Google's quality rater guidelines define YMYL content as anything that could "significantly impact the health, financial stability, or safety of people, or the welfare or well-being of society." The Medic Update was the first major signal that these guidelines would be enforced algorithmically, not just by human quality raters.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why does the Google Medic Update matter?</h2>
        <p>The Medic Update established four non-negotiable principles for anyone publishing on health, finance, legal, or safety topics:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Expertise is now a ranking factor.</strong> Anonymous health advice stopped ranking when hospital content with named physicians was available. The algorithm could distinguish between "I read about this" and "I'm trained in this."</li>
          <li><strong>Author credentials must be visible.</strong> It's not enough to have a qualified writer — their credentials need to appear on the page. A bio saying "John Smith, MD, FACP, 15 years in emergency medicine" signals something Google can evaluate.</li>
          <li><strong>Trust signals matter algorithmically.</strong> HTTPS, a clear contact page, a privacy policy, a detailed "About Us" page, and editorial policies became ranking prerequisites for sensitive topics — not just UX niceties.</li>
          <li><strong>Impact extends beyond health.</strong> Financial services, legal advice, news, and even recipe sites (food safety) fall under YMYL scrutiny. The update's logic applies to any content where getting it wrong could harm a reader.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How does the Medic Update work?</h2>

        <h3>YMYL content classification</h3>
        <p>Google applies a two-tier evaluation to content. "Netflix shows to watch" has low stakes — a bad recommendation wastes an evening. "Treating chest pain at home" has extremely high stakes — a bad recommendation could cost a life. YMYL classification triggers heightened scrutiny on every E-E-A-T signal on the page and across the site.</p>

        <h3>E-E-A-T signal evaluation</h3>
        <p>Sites that recovered from the Medic Update typically implemented these signals:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Detailed author bios with professional credentials listed</li>
          <li>Links to author professional profiles (LinkedIn, medical board listings)</li>
          <li>Medical, legal, or financial expert review of content before publication</li>
          <li>Citations to primary research, peer-reviewed studies, or government sources</li>
          <li>Clear editorial policies explaining the review process</li>
          <li>Comprehensive "About Us" pages with organizational history and staff</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Ongoing enforcement</h3>
        <p>The Medic Update wasn't a one-time event. Its principles are now embedded in Google's core algorithm and reinforced by every subsequent core update. Sites that recovered but then let E-E-A-T signals decay have seen rankings slip again at later updates.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Medic Update vs other Google algorithm updates</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Update</th><th>Year</th><th>What it targeted</th><th>Primary signal</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Medic Update</strong></td>
                <td>2018</td>
                <td>YMYL content without E-E-A-T</td>
                <td>Author credentials + trust signals</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Google Panda</strong></td><td>2011</td><td>Thin and duplicate content</td><td>Content quality ratio</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Google Penguin</strong></td><td>2012</td><td>Manipulative link building</td><td>Link quality and patterns</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Helpful Content Update</strong></td><td>2022</td><td>AI-generated and unhelpful content</td><td>Content written for people, not search engines</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Core Web Vitals</strong></td><td>2021</td><td>Poor page experience</td><td>Load speed, interactivity, visual stability</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real Google Medic Update examples</h2>

        <h3>Natural health blog — the hard hit</h3>
        <p>A wellness blog without medical credentials published "cure diabetes naturally with these 5 herbs." Pre-update, these articles ranked well on content length and backlinks. Post-update, they dropped to page 4+ as Google elevated content from Mayo Clinic, WebMD, and sites with physician-reviewed articles on diabetes management. The problem wasn't just the content — it was the absence of any credential signal that the author was qualified to give medical advice.</p>

        <h3>Financial planning firm — the unexpected winner</h3>
        <p>A regional financial planning firm's blog, written by CFPs and CPAs with credentials listed in every author bio, improved rankings after the update without changing a single piece of content. Their traffic increased 35% while competitors without clear expertise signals declined. Their existing structure — credential listings, citation to IRS publications and financial regulations, detailed "Meet the Team" pages — already met E-E-A-T standards.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Medic Update vs Helpful Content Update — key differences</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Medic Update (2018)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Targeted YMYL content specifically</li>
              <li>Evaluated author expertise and credentials</li>
              <li>Rewarded organizational trust signals</li>
              <li>Required expert review for medical/financial content</li>
              <li>Recovery requires credential additions, not content rewrites</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Helpful Content Update (2022)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Targeted all content types, not just YMYL</li>
              <li>Evaluated whether content was written for people vs search engines</li>
              <li>Penalized AI-generated and thinly edited content at scale</li>
              <li>Required actual helpfulness, not just credential display</li>
              <li>Recovery requires content rewrites or removal</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 E-E-A-T practices the Medic Update rewards</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Name every author and list their credentials.</strong> For medical content: "Dr. Sarah Chen, MD, FACP, 12 years in internal medicine." For financial content: "James Liu, CFP, CFA, 15 years in wealth management." The credential specificity matters.</li>
          <li><strong>Link author bios to verifiable external profiles.</strong> LinkedIn, medical board listings, university faculty pages, and professional association directories all confirm the author exists and holds the claimed credentials.</li>
          <li><strong>Implement expert review for YMYL content.</strong> Add a "Medically reviewed by" or "Reviewed by a certified financial planner" line with reviewer credentials and the review date.</li>
          <li><strong>Cite primary sources visibly.</strong> Link to PubMed studies, CDC guidelines, IRS publications, or peer-reviewed journals — not just other blog posts. AI engines and Google both favor content with verifiable references.</li>
          <li><strong>Build a transparent organizational presence.</strong> A detailed "About Us" page, clear contact information, a named editorial team, and a stated editorial policy are trust signals Google evaluates beyond the individual page.</li>
          <li><strong>Update content with review dates.</strong> Showing "Last reviewed: March 2026 by Dr. Sarah Chen" signals ongoing editorial maintenance — a strong trust signal for time-sensitive health or financial information.</li>
          <li><strong>Remove or improve low-E-E-A-T YMYL pages.</strong> One anonymous, uncited health article can drag down an entire domain's trust score. Audit for these and either upgrade them with expert review or noindex them.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — thinking the Medic Update only affects health sites</div>
          <p>Legal advice, financial planning, nutrition, safety instructions, news, and civic information all fall under YMYL. If your site publishes content where getting the answer wrong could harm a reader — financially, physically, or legally — E-E-A-T signals are non-optional. Anonymous authorship on these topics is a ranking liability regardless of content length or backlink count.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common mistakes the Medic Update exposed</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Anonymous YMYL authorship.</strong> "Staff writer" or "Editorial team" instead of a named, credentialed individual is the most common trigger for E-E-A-T penalties on health and finance sites.</li>
          <li><strong>No citations on factual claims.</strong> Publishing health statistics without linking to the study that produced them undermines credibility Google can evaluate.</li>
          <li><strong>Outdated content without review dates.</strong> A 2019 medical article without an update or review date signals stale information on a high-stakes topic.</li>
          <li><strong>Thin "About Us" pages.</strong> A single paragraph about the company without naming staff, describing credentials, or explaining editorial standards leaves a major trust gap.</li>
          <li><strong>Conflating content quality with E-E-A-T.</strong> A well-written, long article from an anonymous author still lacks E-E-A-T on YMYL topics. Both content quality and credential signals are required.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Does the Medic Update only affect health sites?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>No. It heavily impacted health and medical sites but also affected financial services, legal advice, news, and any YMYL category. Google's quality rater guidelines define YMYL broadly — any content significantly impacting well-being faces heightened scrutiny.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How do I recover from a Medic Update hit?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Add detailed author bios with real credentials. Cite authoritative sources. Get content reviewed by qualified experts. Improve trust signals including HTTPS, contact info, and editorial policies. Remove or update low-quality YMYL content lacking expertise. Recovery typically takes 2-4 core update cycles, or 6-12 months.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Is the Medic Update still active?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Its principles are permanently integrated into Google's core algorithm. Every subsequent core update builds on the same E-E-A-T and YMYL foundations. The Medic Update label is historical, but its impact on how Google evaluates YMYL content remains ongoing.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is YMYL in the context of the Medic Update?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>YMYL stands for Your Money or Your Life. It describes content that could significantly impact a reader's health, financial stability, safety, or legal standing. Google applies heightened quality standards to YMYL topics because inaccurate or low-quality information in these areas causes real-world harm.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
